=== Float Formatting (the %g spec — docs/semantics.md) ===

Floats stringify via C's %g with precision 6, on every backend.
Two variants:
  - show / string_of_float / interpolation: bare %g           (3.0 -> "3")
  - display (final values, print, nested in structures): %g
    plus a trailing "." when the result could otherwise be
    read as an int; inf/nan are unambiguous so no dot          (3.0 -> "3.")

--- test: whole float displays with trailing dot
3.0
--- expect: 3.

--- test: show whole float has no trailing dot
show 3.0
--- expect: 3

--- test: string_of_float whole float has no trailing dot
string_of_float 100.0
--- expect: 100

--- test: string_of_float fractional
string_of_float 2.5
--- expect: 2.5

--- test: string interpolation of whole float
$"{2.0}"
--- expect: 2

--- test: string interpolation of fractional float
$"x = {1.25}"
--- expect: x = 1.25

--- test: float display rounds to six significant digits
123456.789
--- expect: 123457.

--- test: large float displays in scientific notation
1780344245.513
--- expect: 1.78034e+09

--- test: show large float scientific notation
show 1780344245.513
--- expect: 1.78034e+09

--- test: small float scientific notation
0.0000123
--- expect: 1.23e-05

--- test: boundary just below scientific threshold
0.0001
--- expect: 0.0001

--- test: ten billion collapses to one significant digit
10000000000.0
--- expect: 1e+10

--- test: negative large float
0.0 - 1234567.89
--- expect: -1.23457e+06

--- test: float infinity displays bare
1.0 / 0.0
--- expect: inf

--- test: float negative infinity displays bare
0.0 - 1.0 / 0.0
--- expect: -inf

--- test: show of float list uses bare float format
show [3.0; 100.0]
--- expect: [3; 100]

--- test: show of float tuple uses bare float format
show (1.5, 2.0)
--- expect: (1.5, 2)

--- test: float list with decimals displays unchanged
[1.5; 2.25]
--- expect: [1.5; 2.25]

--- test: string_of_float as first-class function
List.map string_of_float [1.5; 2.0]
--- expect: [1.5; 2]

--- test: string_of_bool as direct call
string_of_bool true
--- expect: true

--- test: print of float list uses display format
print [3.0; 100.0];;
()
--- expect: [3.; 100.]

--- test: whole float nested in tuple display
(1.5, 2.0)
--- expect: (1.5, 2.)

--- test: whole float nested in list display
[3.0; 100.0]
--- expect: [3.; 100.]

=== Nested Float Display Tests (BUG-3 regression suite) ===

--- test: whole float in map value display
print #{"a": 2.0};;
()
--- expect: [(a, 2.)]

--- test: whole float in option payload display
print (Some 4.0);;
()
--- expect: Some 4.

--- test: whole float in array display
print #[1.0; 2.5];;
()
--- expect: #[1.; 2.5]

--- test: whole float in record field display
print { alpha = 3.0; beta = "p" };;
()
--- expect: { alpha = 3.; beta = p }

--- test: whole float in nested list of tuples display
print [(1.0, 2); (3.5, 4)];;
()
--- expect: [(1., 2); (3.5, 4)]

--- test: show of nested whole float stays bare
show [3.0; 100.0]
--- expect: [3; 100]

--- test: float list as final value uses display format
[7.0; 8.25]
--- expect: [7.; 8.25]

--- test: variant with float payload as final value
type wrapped = Wrap of float | Empty
Wrap 5.0
--- expect: Wrap 5.

--- test: first-class print falls back to heuristic display
List.iter print [1.5; 2.25];;
()
--- expect: "1.5\n2.25"

=== Math.float_bits_hex — IEEE-754 bit pattern as uppercase hex ===

The 64-bit IEEE-754 representation of a double, uppercase, no leading zeros,
no prefix (matches OCaml Printf "%LX" of Int64.bits_of_float). Used by the
native backend to emit exact float constants; verified equal on every backend.

--- test: float_bits_hex 1.0
Math.float_bits_hex 1.0
--- expect: 3FF0000000000000

--- test: float_bits_hex 0.0
Math.float_bits_hex 0.0
--- expect: 0

--- test: float_bits_hex negative
Math.float_bits_hex (0.0 - 1.0)
--- expect: BFF0000000000000

--- test: float_bits_hex 2.0
Math.float_bits_hex 2.0
--- expect: 4000000000000000

--- test: float_bits_hex 0.5
Math.float_bits_hex 0.5
--- expect: 3FE0000000000000

--- test: float_bits_hex 3.14
Math.float_bits_hex 3.14
--- expect: 40091EB851EB851F

=== Variable-precision float formatting (__fmt_float_g / __fmt_float) ===

These back the formatter's float_lit (shortest round-tripping decimal).
__fmt_float_g is C "%.*g" (N significant digits, %g style); __fmt_float is
C "%.*f" (N decimal places). Cross-backend agreement is what lets the
self-host formatter (emit-js) match the OCaml reference byte-for-byte.

--- test: fmt_float_g 1 sig digit of zero
__fmt_float_g 1 0.0
--- expect: 0

--- test: fmt_float_g 6 sig digits
__fmt_float_g 6 3.14159
--- expect: 3.14159

--- test: fmt_float_g 2 sig digits rounds
__fmt_float_g 2 3.14159
--- expect: 3.1

--- test: fmt_float_g switches to exponent when X >= prec
__fmt_float_g 3 1000000.0
--- expect: 1e+06

--- test: fmt_float_g fixed-point at exponent boundary
__fmt_float_g 4 0.0001234
--- expect: 0.0001234

--- test: fmt_float_g exponent below -4
__fmt_float_g 2 0.00001
--- expect: 1e-05

--- test: fmt_float fixed 3 decimals
__fmt_float 3 3.14159
--- expect: 3.142

--- test: fmt_float zero decimals rounds
__fmt_float 0 3.7
--- expect: 4
